PSEUDOCODE
==========

Initialize SysTick, USART2 TX+RX, PA5 LED
Enable RXNE interrupt in USART2->CR1
Enable USART2 IRQ in NVIC

Implement a circular ring buffer (head, tail, buffer[N])

In USART2 ISR:
    If RXNE set:
        Read byte from RDR -> clears RXNE
        Write byte into ring buffer at head
        Advance head
    If ORE set:
        Clear it via ICR

In main loop:
    If ring buffer not empty:
        Read byte from tail
        Advance tail
        Process command (same table as Program 11)
        Act on LED / send UART response

    Non-blocking LED blink via ms_ticks

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA2  ->  USART2_TX (AF1)
PA3  ->  USART2_RX (AF1)
PA5  ->  LED (GPIO output)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

USART2 (Universal Synchronous/Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter)
|-------------|---------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register    | Field         | Description                                                                     |
|-------------|---------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| USART2->CR1 | bit5 RXNEIE   | RX Not Empty Interrupt Enable. When set, fires USART2 IRQ every time RXNE sets. |
| USART2->CR1 | bit3 RXOVRDIE | Not used here - ORE handling done in ISR by checking ISR register directly.     |
| USART2->ISR | bit5 RXNE     | Still the flag that triggers the interrupt. Reading RDR clears it.              |
| USART2->ISR | bit3 ORE      | Overrun - checked inside ISR and cleared immediately via ICR.                   |
| USART2->ICR | bit3 ORECF    | Write 1 to clear ORE.                                                           |
|-------------|---------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

NVIC (Nested Vectored Interrupt Controller)
|------------|-------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register   | Field             | Description                                                             |
|------------|-------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| NVIC->ISER | bit28 USART2_IRQn | USART2 is IRQ28 on STM32G071. Enable here to receive USART2 interrupts. |
|------------|-------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Power-of-2 buffer size enables maskless wrap -> (index + 1) & (SIZE - 1) is a
  single AND instruction - no division, no branch, no libgcc. If we use a
  non-power-of-2 size, we need a comparison and conditional reset, which is
  slightly more code. Always use power-of-2 for ring buffers on bare-metal.

* Head and tail are volatile but the buffer itself needs care. The head and tail
  indices are volatile because the ISR writes head and main reads it. The buffer
  array itself does not need volatile because access is always gated through the
  index check. However the struct is declared volatile overall here - be aware
  that this forces the compiler to re-read every element every time, which is
  safe but slightly less optimal.

* wfi and ring buffer, ordering matters. The sequence must always be: check
  buffer -> process -> wfi. If we do wfi first, we may sleep through a byte that
  arrived just before wfi executed but after the last buffer check. The
  Cortex-M0+ guarantees that if an interrupt is pending when wfi executes, it
  wakes immediately, so this ordering is safe as long as RXNEIE is enabled
  before the loop.

* ISR sending UART bytes - avoid it. It might be tempting to echo bytes directly
  from the ISR. The problem: usart2_send_byte polls TXE in a loop, and if the
  UART is busy, we spin inside the ISR blocking everything else. Always push to
  a buffer in the ISR and transmit in the main loop.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* This is the correct production pattern for UART RX. Polling RXNE in the main
  loop (Program 11) works only when the loop is fast enough. The
  interrupt-driven ring buffer works regardless of how slow or busy the main
  loop is, as long as the buffer does not overflow. The buffer size of 16 bytes
  handles bursts of fast typing easily at 115200 baud.

* The ring buffer is a universal bare-metal construct. The exact same RingBuffer
  structure with head written by producer and tail read by consumer appears in
  ADC streaming, DMA completion queuing, and any other ISR-to-main data
  handoff. It is worth memorising this pattern cold.

* Why wfi still makes sense here. Even with interrupt-driven RX, the main loop
  has nothing to do between characters arriving. wfi saves power and reduces EMI
  from unnecessary instruction fetches. The USART2 interrupt wakes the core the
  instant a byte arrives, response latency is one interrupt entry cycle, not one
  full loop iteration.

* Two-state machine vs full command processor. The BLINK_STATE / MANUAL_STATE
  state machine here is minimal. A production UART command processor would
  typically have a third state for multi-character commands (e.g. SET 750\r\n to
  set blink interval to 750ms), buffering characters until \r or \n, then
  parsing the full line. That line-buffer pattern builds naturally on top of
  this ring buffer foundation.
